Story
A comedy-drama television series produced in the United States in 2006, Psych tells the tale of Shawn Spencer, a young man who poses as a psychic to assist the Santa Barbara Police Department in solving crimes. They use their special talents and sense of humour to solve challenging situations with the assistance of Gus, his best friend.

Psych Review

Psych is a comedy-drama television series that premiered in 2006 and ran for eight seasons. Created by Steve Franks, the show follows the adventures of Shawn Spencer (James Roday Rodriguez), a young man who poses as a psychic to assist the Santa Barbara Police Department in solving crimes. Along with his best friend Gus (DulÃ© Hill), Shawn uses his keen observation skills and sense of humor to solve cases that often leave the police stumped. The show's unique blend of comedy and drama makes it a joy to watch, with each episode delivering laughs and suspense in equal measure. TRIVIA AND POPULAR DIALOGUES

Trivia

As a running gag, in every episode, you'll find a pineapple, the word "delicious", a fist bump, the phrase, "I can't do this right now", and the question "What?"

After the series finale, the Blueberry was given away to the highest bidder. It was signed by James Roday and Dulé Hill on the passenger side mirror.

Inspired by how series creator Steve Franks' father, who was a Los Angeles police officer, would teach him how to be observant.

James Roday (Shawn Spencer) and Maggie Lawson (Juliet O'Hara) started dating during the filming of season one. Their relationship lasted seven years.

In the final episode, "The Break-Up", Chief Vick and Juilet mentioned that they can't hire Psych as a consulting team, because they already have a guy, and he is "alphabetizing the pantry as we speak". This is a reference to the television show Monk (2002), which was set in San Francisco, California.
